{"/service/ndnp/arhi/batch_arhi_beatles_ver01/data/sn89051084/00393342705/1908060501/0617.xml":{"full_text":"Published In The Famous White Riven Country. Where Alfalfa Is King\n$1 Per Annum\nNewark, Independence County, Arkansas, Friday, June 5, 1908\nVol. 8. No. 24\nEDUCATIONAL EXHIBIT\nEducators Interested in Making Fine\nShowing at Coming State Fair\nOne of the most important, largest\nand most attractive features of the\nThird Annual State Fair and Indus\ntrial Exposition of Arkarsas to be\nheld at Hot Springs, October 12 to 17,\nwill be the gigantic, composite educa\ntional exhibit.\nThe schools, colleges, universities\nand seats of learning of every class\nare being interested in the educational\ndepartment of the state fair, which\nwill be under the management of Prof.\nGeo. B. C'ook, Democratic nominee\nfor state superintendent of public in\nstruction.\nRepresentative work of the pupils\nof all classes of schools will be ac\nceptable, as well as pictures of school\nbuildings, groups of scholars, etc.\nThis work can be sent now to the edu\ncational department of the Arkansas\nFair, Hot Springs, Ark. It is only\n(required that the exhibits lie sent pre\npaid with full instructions as to their\nreturn after the close of the state fair.\nm Liberal awards in books, diplomas,\netc., will be given for all creditable\nwork.\nThe fair association has set aside a\nlarge and centrally located space for\nthe school exhibits, and this will l>e\none of the several interesting, valua\nble and instructive features of the in\ndustrial division of the next state fair.\nCHARLOTTE CHRONICLES\nCharlotte, .Tune 2.\u2014Mr. and Mrs.\nEll>ert Reeves of Oil Trough visited\nMr. and Mrs. Joe Kent at this place\nSaturday night, and attended the\nChildrens Day services Sunday.\nSam and Charles Moore and sister.\nMiss Josie. and Mis# Parilee Foster\nwent to Batesvilie Friday.\nMiss Bonnie Huddleston of Sulphur\nRock visited her cousin, Miss Clara\nMcGill here last week.\nMiss Sallie Nuckolls and brother,\nTommy, made a business trip to\nBatesvilie Saturday.\nMiss Nettye Bevens of Sulphur\nRock visited Mrs. Wilma Baker a few\ndays last week.\nMiss Younger of Cave City is visit\ning Miss Beryl Ward this week.\nWash Herrington of Newark is vis\niting Owen Walden here this week.\nA large crowd attended Childrens\nDay here Sunday.\nSTRANGE THINGS HAPPEN\nYou cannot always sometimes tell\nwhat will happen. For instance, here\nis a story of an Oklahoma man who\ndetermined to commit suicide: He went\nto the store and bought a roj>e, a can\nof oil, a box of matches, a dose of ar\nsenic and a revolver. He went to the\nriver, pushed his boat out from the\nshore and paddled down to where a\nlimb hung over, then got up in the\nbow of the boat and tied one end of the\nrope to the limb and the other about\nhis neck, took a dose of arsenic, sat\nurated his clothing with oil and set\nthem on fire, put the muzzle of the re\nvolver against his temple and pulled\nthe trigger. But the bullet glanced\nand cut the rope above him and he fell\nkerwallop into the river. The water\nput out the fire, and he got strangled\nand coughed up the arsenic. The water\nwas not deep enough to drown him,\nso he waded out and declared himself\na candidate for office on the populist\nticket.\nOLD LANDMARK GONE\nThe old frame building on the cor\nner of South and Brgfod streets, known\nas the old Hughes property, and own\ned by Dr. J. W. Case, has been torn\ndown. Dr. Case does not contemplate\nrebuilding soon, but will at some\nfuture time erect a business house\nthere. The site, is' one of the most\ndesirable in the city.\nThe old house just torn dow n was\nbuilt seventy-five years ago, and Dr.\nCase bought the property in 1878.\nWhen he bought it the house stood on\n^\u2019hat is now Broad street, and Dr.\nCase moved it over to where it has\nbeen many years and sold the street to\nthe city.\u2014Batesville Guard.\nSULPHUR ROCK HAPPENINGS\nItems of Interest Picked up at the Hub\nof White River Township\nSulphur Rock. June 2. Mrs. J. \\1.\nHoover of Newark and her son, O. L.\nHoover, of this place, spent a day or\ntwo the latter part of last week at\nCathevtown visiting1 Mrs. Hoover\u2019s\ndaughter, Mrs. Ward.\nMrs. Jas. F. Jernigan and children,\nPaul and Willeen, of Newark, were\nvisiting in town Saturday and went to\nCharlotte to attend the Childrens' Day\nservices Sunday.\nRev. E. A. Horn preached a very\ninteresting sermon to the Masons at\nthe M. E. church Sunday. He also\npreached Sunday night.\nRev. and Mrs.C. F. Hively and little\ndaughter, Millie, went to Rosie Satur\nday, where Rev. Hively tilled his ap\npointment Sunday.\nMrs. T. J. Brannon and daughter,\nMiss Nora, and Mrs. J. P. Magness\nof Newark were shopping in town\nSaturday.\nMiss Bea Rice spent last week with\nher grand parents. Mrs. and Mr. H.\nF. McDoniel, in the Dota neighbor\nhood.\nkidney Pickens left Tuesday night\nfor Little Rock where he will attend\nthe State Sunday School Convention.\nQuite a numlier of our people attend\ned Childrens' Day services at Char\nlotte Sunday and report a nice time.\nMiss Vela Jernigan of Charlott spent\nSunday nigdit here with her cousin,\nMiss Irene Huddleston.\nChildrens' Day services at the Bap\ntist church next Sunday, June 7. Ser\nvices open at 9:30 a. m.\nNo wonder cotton patches look so\nclean, when Ed and Stripe have been\nswinging the goose neck.\nA number of boys and girls from\nhere spent a delightful day a Char\nlotte Sunday.\nMrs. Braden went to Newport Mon\nday night to visit her daughter, Mrs.\nBerry Best.\nOscar Lee and a Miss Stevens were\nmarried at the parsonage Sunday\nmorning.\nWhen a woman says, \u2018Tret's make\na garden,\u201d a garden is, made. Ask\nPickens.\nBen Keeney a merchant at Sharp,\nwas in town on business Monday.\nProf. Sidney Pickens and Tom Gib\nson went to Newark Monday.\nJ. Kf Rawlings visited his father\nnear Charlotte Friday.\nEdgar Rodgers of Sharp was visit\nting here Sunday.\nW. N. Osborne of Cord spent Sun\nday in our town.\nMrs. W. S. Moore is sick at the\npresent writing.\nGeo. Bevens was down from Bates\nville Saturday.\nFaris Rice spent a few days at New\nport last weed.\nJeff Edward was up from Newark\nSaturday.\nJ. H. Rodgers was down from Sharp\nMonday.\nJ. C. Huddleston went to Batesville\nTuesday.\nRev. Horn went to Batesville Mon\nday.\nBUSINESS AND POLITICS\nThe business interests of the country\nare much more concerned about the\nreturn of prosperity than they are\nabout the men who are to lead in the\npresidential sweepstake. We can stand\nmost anythin# in politics that does\nnot interfere with business. The hum\nof machinery sounds sweeter to the\naverage business man than the music\nof the political orator, and really there\nIs more in it.\u2014Paro#ould Soliphone.\nCOUNTY UNION MEETING\nThe Independence County Union F.\nE. C. U. of A., will meet in regular\nsession June 26 and 27, 1908, with\nCorrier Stone Local Union No. 1075,\nlocated four miles east of Pleasant\nPlains.\nA full delegation is desired. The\nUnion will open at 10 o\u2019clock a. m.\nFriday, the first da^\nW. D. Bullington, Sec.-Treas!\ni*\nte,\nEX-SENATOR JONES DEAD\n\nNoted Arkansan Passed Away at His\nHome in Washington City\nFormer United States Senator J. K.\nJones of Arkansas died at his resi\ndence in Washington, I). C., Monday,\nafter an illness of only a few hours.\nSenator Jones was one of the lead\ning Democrats itflhe senate from 188o\nto 1903, and was one of the strongest\nsupporters of Bryan, having, as\nchairman of the Democratic National\nCommittee, conducted the campaigns\nof 189(1 and 19(X).\nSince leaving the Senate in 1903 he\nhas conducted a law practice in Wash\ning City and has not actively engaged\nin politics.\nOn Friday Senator Jones returned\nfrom a visit to his daughter, Mrs.\nLeonora Carrington, in Arkansas, and\nSunday night was apparently enjoying\ngood health. Comnlaing slightly Mon\nday morning, he remain in bed and at\n5:3<\u00bb p. m. died, the immediate cauje\nof death l)eing heart failure.\nSenator Jones was a delegate to the\nNational Democratic Convention of\n189(1, which gave Mr. Bryan his first\nnomination, and as chairman of the\nCommittee on Resolutions he reported\nthe lti-to-1 platform. He was made\nchairman of the National Democratic\nCommittee after the convention and\nas such conducted both of the Bryan\ncampaigns for the presidency.\nSenator Jones was (19 years old and\nis survived by his widow and three\nchildren, Mrs. Carrington, of Arkan\nsas: Miss Sue Jones and James K.\nJones, Jr. Senator Jone^w as buried\nin Washington City.\nNOTICE FOR NEW ROAD\nNotice is hereby given that a j>eti\ntion will be presented to the Indepen\ndence County Court, July term, l!H)8,\nfor an order appointing viewers to\nview, survey, and lay out a new public\nroad in Logan township. Said road\ndescribed as follows:\nBeginning at the section corners of\nSections 13 and 14, 23 and 24, town\nship 13 North, range 4 west, running\nwest on section lines to intersect the\nNewark and Cord road on the east\nside of Dota creek.\nJNO. H. Fktzkr,\nC. E. .flMERSON,\nJ. E. McCoy,\nWilliam Bradley\nMay 30, 1008. and Others.\nBIG BOTTOM FARM FOR SALE\nWe have for sale one of the finest\nfarms in the famous Big Bottom, only\n34 miles from Newark, consisting of\n342 acres, 250 acres of which is in culti\nvation, and produces 50 to 75 bushels\nof corn or a bale of cotton per acre.\nThis is one of the finest farms in\nBig Bottom which is noted for its\nimmense yields of cotton, corn and\nalfalfa.\nThere are five tenant houses on the\nfarm, of two to four rooms each and\ntwo good large box barns.\nA genuine bargain if taken at once.\nHenderson Real Estate Co., Newark.\nArk.\nHANGED HIMSELF IN JAIL\nJerome Wells, who killed John VV.\nBaker several months ago, hanged\nhimself in jail at Mountain Home,\nusing baling wire, some time on the\nnight of May 30th. When the turnkey\nbrought the prisoners their breakfast\nin the morning he found Well\u2019s body\nhanging by a rope of wire, which he\nhad taken from the stove-pipe that it\nheld up, and braided together. The\nbody was cold when found, and it is\nthought that he committed the deed in\nthe middle of the night.\nDISTRICT UNION\nThe N. E. District Union F. E. C.\nU. of A. will meet with Mountain Gap\nUnion the first Saturday in June. All\nlocal unions are urged to send full\ndelegation. T. A. Buli-inuton,\nSecretary.\nNOTARY PUBLIC\nNotary work of all kinds done in a\ncareful and correct manner by A. A.\nHenderson at the Merchants and\nPlanters Bank.\nTHE 1908 COTTON CROP\nGovernment Report Indicates Slight\nIncrease in Acreage This Year\nThe cotton planted this spring is\nestimated at 112,081,OOO acres, and its\ncondition on May 2a last, is given as\n70.7 per cent, in the first cotton re\nports for this season made public by\nthe Departmen of Agriculture at\nWashington Tuesday. The acreage\nas estimated is against 32,000,000 acres\nlast year and the condition on May 25\nis against 70.5 last year.\nThe area as given includes that al\nready planted and expected to l\u00bbe\nplanted, and is about one-tenth of one\nj>er cent greater than the area planted\nlast year. The condition of the grow\ning crop on May 25, l!\u00ab)(i, was 84.6 per\ncent of a normal and the average of\nthe condition May 25 for the past ten\nyears was 82.5 per cent.\nThe estimated area planted and to\nbe planted in cotton 1908 and condi\ntion by states follows.\nState. Acreage. 'ondition.\nVirginia. .'17,000 88\nNorth Carolina. 1,427,000 87\nSouth Carolina.2,465,000 81\nGeorgia_4,775,000 80\nFlorida.. 268,000 82\nAlabama_5,509,000 78\nMississippi.5,252,000 80\nLouisiana_1,656,000 80\nTexas..9,523,000 77\nArkansas_2,011,000 85\nTennessee_ 757,000 84\nMissouri_ 74,000 86\nOklahoma _.2,059,000 80\nMEETING AT HEBER\nEditor Journal: We are beginning\nto move up towards the great meetings\nat Newark, Sulphur llock and Lee's\nChapel. Sunday was a great day.\nThere were four accessions and at\nnight fully two dozen came for prayer.\nGreat crowds and much interest. Pas\ntor F. P. Jernigan is very popular\nwith, not/ only his own people, but\nwith the entire town. This town is on\na rush: building after building going\nup everywhere. I counted 21 residences\ngoing up and did not go the town over.\nHave met our Newarkers, who seem to\nbe getting along nicely; John D. Ayde\nlotte, Nick Speed and others. Labe,\nTom and Kate are all getting along\nroyally. Labe can talk \u201cwashing\u201d\nequal to an expert. Don\u2019t know when\n\"i\u2019ll l>e at home, but Friday I suppose.\nBut it will take till frost to round up\nthis great work now in progress. Hoj>e\nall are well. 1 am having plenty to\ndo and plenty to eat. Meet many old\nfriends, some of whom I have known\nnearly 30 years.\nJames F. Jernigan.\nFARM FOR SALE\nGood farm of 100 acres near High\nRock, 11 miles north of Batesville, 75\nacres in cultivation 25 acres of which\nis tine creek bottom land which grows\n75 bushels of corn j>er acre. Good\nframe dwelling with two tenant houses.\nTwo orchards with an abundant varie\nty of fruits. Good oak, hickory and\ncedar timber on land not in cultiva\ntion. Fine water, both well and spring,\nwith fine creek running through farm.\nGood mill-site on farm. Fine cave\nnear dwelling where 10,(KM) pushels of\nvegetables may l>e kept the year round.\nConvenient to school and church.\nWill be sold cheap and on easy terms.\nHenderson Real Estate Co., Newark\nArk.\nARKANSAS BAPTIST SUED\nRev. R. J. Mathews, formerly pastor\nof the Park avenue Baptist church at\nHot Springs, has tiled suit against the\nArkansas Baptist of Little Rock for\n$20,000 for the publication of an article\nconcerning him and a Miss Mabel\nColeman, which he alleges has affected\nhis reputation as an evangelist and\ninjured his ability to make a living\nfor his family.\nJOHN KEEL WINS\nThe sub-committee of the State Cen\ntral Democratic Committee appointed\nto investigate the contest between\nLipman and Keel in the Twenty-ninth\nSenatorial district, met at Little Rock\nSaturday, and after investigating the\nmatter decided in favor John Keel.\nDEMOCRATIC CONVENTION\nFeature of State Convention was Frost\nGiven Senator Jeff Davis\nThe Democratic State Convention in\nsession at Little Rock Tuesday and\nWednesday had hut little to do except\ncarry out the wishes of the party as\nexpressed in the March primary.\nAbout the only mattefof interest to\ncome before the convention was the\nelection of delegates to the national\nconvention and the framing' of a plat\nform.\nThe big four elected by the conven\ntion as delegates-at-large are Senator\nJas. P. Clarke, Geo. W. Donaghey,\nO. C. Ludwig- and J. H.'Harrod.\nThe district delegates are as follows:\nFirst\u2014J. T. Robinson of Marianna\nand W. J. Lamb of Osceola.\nSecond\u2014Dr. C. E. Pringle of Poca\nhontas and Gustave Jones of Newport.\nThird\u2014Jerry South of Mountain\nHome and Claude Fuller of Eureka\nSprings.\nFourth\u2014Samuel Chew of Van Buren\nand Jeff Sanderson of Texarkana.\nFifth\u2014Joseph W. House of Little\nRock and Emmett E. Mitchell of Mor\nrilton.\nnixm-jonn r mitnerioru oi fine\nBluff and T. C. Hughes of Malvern.\nSeventh\u2014Thomas J. Going of Cam\nden and John Crawford of Ajdcadel\nphia.\nThe feature of the convention was\nthe frost given Senator Jeff Davis who\nwas present and ps a candidate fop\na place on the lug four delegation.\nWhen placed in nomination for dele\ngate, Davis\u2019 name was hissed and\nJudge Kvans who nominated him was\nhissed and howled at until he was\nforced to sit down without finishing his\nnominating speech.\nThe platform adopted includes the\nfollowing declarations:\nIndorses W. J. Bryan for president;\ndemands an anti-pass law: favors con\nservation 6f State\u2019s resources, recla\nmation of swamp lands, development\nof inland waterways, enactment of\ngeneral laws only, better roads, anew\nbanking law, establishment of agricul\ntural schools, protection of labor, de\nvelopment of State\u2019s resources, pro\nmotion of education interests, suppres\nsion of gambling, increase of the pow\ners of the Railroad Commission, the\ninitiative and referendum, liberal ap\npropriations for Confederate pensions,\npublicity of campaign expenses, re\nmoval of all persons engaged in build\ning the new State Capital, increased\npay for the judiciary, barring as elec\ntion officers jiersons engaged in the\nmanufacture or sale of liquor, and\nsubmitting the question of State-wide\nprohibition to the jieople at a social\nelection in 1909.\nBLOODY TRAGEDY\nStuttgart, June 2.\u2014One of the most\natrocious murders ever committed in.\nthis county took place this morning'\nnear Crooked bayou on a plantation\nknown as the raig place. Hen Oliver\nshot aud killed his sister, Mrs. Stan\nley, who was setting out sweet potato\nplants in the garden. He then went\ninto the house and shot Stanley, who\nwas in bed sick. Oliver left, but as\nhe climbed over a fence 100 yards from\nthe house, his gun was discharged,\nmaking a fearful wound. He was\npicked up and brought to Stuttgart*\nHis wounds were dressed and he was\nturned over to the sheriff, who took\nhim to the county seat at De Witt.\nThe only reason that Oliver could\ngive for his crime was that his sister\nhad been wronged. He lagged those\nattending him here to cut his throat.\n301 PARDONED IN A YEAR\nFigures recently complied at the sec\nretary of state\u2019s office at Little Rock\nshow\u2019 that 301 pardon\u2019s have been\ngranted from the governor's office dur\ning the last year.\nActing Governor X. O. Pindall,\njrince taking the governors office, has\npardoned 240 persons. Gov. John S.\nLittle, during the short time he was at\nthe head of the state, pardoned ona\nperson: Acting Governor John Ik\u00a9\nMoore pardoned 39 and Acting Gov\nernor Allen H. Hamiter, during the\nfew days he occupied the chair, par\ndoned 15. In all .'101 persons hav\u00a9\nbeen pardoned in about a year\u2019s time.","height":"28532","width":"18812"}}
